      "To effectively monitor an electrical system, you must select instruments based on the specific unit you are measuring.",
      "Remember that some instruments measure what is happening at a single moment, while others track data over a period of time.",
      "The naming convention (Unit + Meter) is your primary guide for selection."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are inspecting a motor. You need to measure the electrical pressure (Volts) at the terminals, the resistance (Ohms) of the internal coils while the power is off, and the total electricity used (kWh) over an 8-hour shift. Name the three specific instruments required for these tasks and explain why an Energy Meter is the correct choice for the final measurement rather than a Wattmeter.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "The three instruments are the Voltmeter, Ohmmeter, and Energy Meter (or kWh meter).",
      "An Energy Meter is required because it measures the cumulative total of electricity consumed over time (kWh), whereas a Wattmeter only measures the instantaneous rate of power (Watts) at a single moment."
    ],
    "hint": "Match the units (Volts, Ohms, kWh) to their meters. Think about which meter acts like a car's odometer to track total 'distance' or usage over the whole shift."
